WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.620
Thank

00:00:13.620 --> 00:00:21.800
you

00:00:21.800 --> 00:00:29.980
.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:43.620
Thank

00:00:43.620 --> 00:00:51.800
you

00:00:51.800 --> 00:00:59.980
.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:02.480
I can tell you a little bit about my two.

00:01:02.480 --> 00:01:05.140
This is a star cluster that's about 3,000 light

00:01:05.140 --> 00:01:05.880
years away.

00:01:05.880 --> 00:01:07.940
My research is all about star clusters.

00:01:07.940 --> 00:01:10.820
These stars here formed like a million years ago.

00:01:10.820 --> 00:01:14.060
This image was taken recently by the European Southern Observatory at

00:01:14.060 --> 00:01:15.580
one of their telescopes in Chile.

00:01:15.580 --> 00:01:18.900
Here you see these kind of stars forming and interacting with the

00:01:18.900 --> 00:01:21.420
interstellar medium and all kinds of stuff.

00:01:22.060 --> 00:01:25.620
And I think that that answers why astronomy exists.

00:01:25.620 --> 00:01:28.180
And it's because we are the outreach of Department of Science

00:01:28.180 --> 00:01:28.380
.

00:01:28.380 --> 00:01:32.770
We can get people so interested and so engaged with science and

00:01:32.770 --> 00:01:33.940
technology.

00:01:33.940 --> 00:01:36.120
Most people who see, say, I don't know,

00:01:36.120 --> 00:01:38.620
Pages of Hubble, learn about astro in school or

00:01:38.620 --> 00:01:41.010
something like that, they're not going to do astro

00:01:41.010 --> 00:01:42.800
as a career because we're such a small field.

00:01:43.040 --> 00:01:45.420
But we can get people engaged with science.

00:01:46.860 --> 00:01:50.570
And as you can imagine, we need kind of effective ways

00:01:50.570 --> 00:01:53.420
to be able to do this kind of outreach.

00:01:53.420 --> 00:01:57.260
And some of these previous platforms, such as Twitter, which

00:01:57.260 --> 00:02:01.060
have now been destroyed by billionaires, it's quite frustrating

00:02:01.060 --> 00:02:03.260
that that's a process that can happen for us as such

00:02:03.260 --> 00:02:05.680
a kind of very strongly outreach driven science.

00:02:05.940 --> 00:02:09.200
It really screws us over that we miss out on these spaces

00:02:09.200 --> 00:02:12.220
when they can just get destroyed effectively.

00:02:12.220 --> 00:02:15.100
But as well as that, it's also not about outreach

00:02:15.100 --> 00:02:15.380
.

00:02:15.380 --> 00:02:19.340
Twitter was a really, really nice space for networking that would

00:02:19.340 --> 00:02:22.220
be really nice to have back and be able to use again

00:02:22.220 --> 00:02:22.580
.

00:02:22.580 --> 00:02:24.910
And it's really a shame that we're kind of missing

00:02:24.910 --> 00:02:25.680
out on this.

00:02:25.680 --> 00:02:28.100
I know through my own PhD, it was so useful to

00:02:28.100 --> 00:02:30.980
have what we call astro Twitter and that that doesn't

00:02:30.980 --> 00:02:32.080
exist anymore.

00:02:32.200 --> 00:02:36.140
There's so much kind of collective community knowledge and this huge

00:02:36.140 --> 00:02:39.160
collective space that we've lost effectively.

00:02:39.160 --> 00:02:42.360
So as it turns out, that protocol is a fantastic,

00:02:42.360 --> 00:02:44.520
fantastic tool for outreach.

00:02:44.520 --> 00:02:46.760
It's something that I and our project has been involved with

00:02:46.760 --> 00:02:47.860
for the last three years.

00:02:47.860 --> 00:02:50.450
So in July of 2023, I started out by making an

00:02:50.450 --> 00:02:51.500
astronomy feed.

00:02:51.500 --> 00:02:55.030
It was partly to procrastinate from preparing for my PhD thesis

00:02:55.030 --> 00:02:55.760
defense.

00:02:56.360 --> 00:02:58.820
But basically, the way that it works is that it collects

00:02:58.820 --> 00:03:02.540
posts from astronomers, astronomy organizations and astrophotographers.

00:03:02.540 --> 00:03:04.390
Effectively, you have to do a little bit of a

00:03:04.390 --> 00:03:06.440
sign up step just to verify that you're who you say

00:03:06.440 --> 00:03:07.000
you are.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:09.060
But then you get to post to this feed.

00:03:09.060 --> 00:03:12.820
Over time, this is developed into what we call an ecosystem

00:03:12.820 --> 00:03:13.640
of feeds.

00:03:13.640 --> 00:03:17.700
We have 15 different feeds that cover all kinds of different topics

00:03:17.700 --> 00:03:20.040
in astronomy and astrophotography.

00:03:20.680 --> 00:03:22.560
And people can kind of self-select where they'd

00:03:22.560 --> 00:03:24.340
like their posts to go by using, say, emojis

00:03:24.340 --> 00:03:25.940
and hashtags and other things.

00:03:25.940 --> 00:03:28.530
And as well as that, I think as a scientist,

00:03:28.530 --> 00:03:31.840
this graph is really boring because it's really flat.

00:03:31.840 --> 00:03:33.540
But it's really cool that it's boring.

00:03:33.540 --> 00:03:36.310
In April of last year, one of our developers added some

00:03:36.310 --> 00:03:37.740
logging to our servers.

00:03:38.400 --> 00:03:40.920
And actually, the stats are kind of boring.

00:03:40.920 --> 00:03:43.140
Like, our views have been stable over time.

00:03:43.140 --> 00:03:45.540
The amount of scrolls that we get on the feeds has

00:03:45.540 --> 00:03:47.480
been relatively stable over time.

00:03:47.480 --> 00:03:50.880
But I think boring is good in this case because we consistently

00:03:50.880 --> 00:03:54.880
have about 15,000 unique people who scroll the feed every

00:03:54.880 --> 00:03:55.380
week.

00:03:55.380 --> 00:03:57.020
So that's not just that the app is kind of pre

00:03:57.020 --> 00:03:59.360
loading the feed or something because the view counts aren't

00:03:59.360 --> 00:04:00.600
necessarily so reliable.

00:04:00.600 --> 00:04:03.290
Though it's really cool we get three quarters of a million

00:04:03.290 --> 00:04:04.440
of a view every week.

00:04:04.720 --> 00:04:08.180
But there's 15,000 people who are really actively engaging

00:04:08.180 --> 00:04:11.480
with this and scrolling through at least 20 posts each week.

00:04:11.480 --> 00:04:13.000
And that's really cool.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:15.170
That's quite a lot of people and quite a big audience

00:04:15.170 --> 00:04:15.380
.

00:04:15.380 --> 00:04:17.510
Especially when for you as an astronomer or astrophot

00:04:17.510 --> 00:04:19.520
ographer, all you have to do is a little sign-

00:04:19.520 --> 00:04:21.080
up process to be able to post there.

00:04:21.080 --> 00:04:23.210
And then you suddenly get to be able to reach this large

00:04:23.210 --> 00:04:26.280
audience who are going to be interested and engaged in the content

00:04:26.280 --> 00:04:27.820
that you want to post about.

00:04:28.820 --> 00:04:31.550
Another thing that's really exciting here too is that we've

00:04:31.550 --> 00:04:34.270
had some relatively good institutional buy-in from a lot of

00:04:34.270 --> 00:04:35.300
past organizations.

00:04:35.300 --> 00:04:37.830
Across both, say, the EU and in the US,

00:04:37.830 --> 00:04:41.540
there have been various orgs that have joined the feeds.

00:04:41.540 --> 00:04:44.680
Some really big names here, for instance, like the European

00:04:44.680 --> 00:04:48.170
Space Agency or the Space Telescope Science Institute, which probably

00:04:48.170 --> 00:04:48.760
none of you know.

00:04:48.840 --> 00:04:51.680
But they run things like Hubble and the Roman Telescope.

00:04:51.680 --> 00:04:53.960
They're a super, super important organization in the US.

00:04:53.960 --> 00:04:55.960
ESO, who I showed you a gorgeous picture from,

00:04:55.960 --> 00:04:58.460
and also the Rubin Observatory, which started taking data

00:04:58.460 --> 00:05:00.380
like a month ago, which is super exciting.

00:05:00.380 --> 00:05:02.080
They're also really active there.

00:05:02.080 --> 00:05:04.600
And that's really nice as well then because you have not

00:05:04.600 --> 00:05:07.800
only astrophotographers and astronomers, but also these like

00:05:07.800 --> 00:05:11.560
really large astronomy organizations all in the kind of same place and

00:05:11.560 --> 00:05:13.140
in one community together.

00:05:13.500 --> 00:05:16.440
And I think often as well where these larger orgs go

00:05:16.440 --> 00:05:18.240
, people might follow too.

00:05:18.240 --> 00:05:20.990
So it's really, really nice that these organizations have been

00:05:20.990 --> 00:05:23.590
interested in joining Blue Sky, that they found our feeds,

00:05:23.590 --> 00:05:26.160
and that they got involved, and that they post there.

00:05:26.160 --> 00:05:28.220
We're a bit of a tech conference, so I'll

00:05:28.220 --> 00:05:31.080
mention briefly as well what we're doing in terms of tech

00:05:31.080 --> 00:05:32.080
stack things.

00:05:32.560 --> 00:05:35.070
Most of our back end is actually running in Python, which

00:05:35.070 --> 00:05:37.340
I don't think is very common for most projects.

00:05:37.340 --> 00:05:40.260
The choice with that is because Python is the most common language

00:05:40.260 --> 00:05:42.470
in astronomy, and it makes it easier for us to kind

00:05:42.470 --> 00:05:44.700
of interact with the astronomy community.

00:05:44.700 --> 00:05:47.710
There's a really nice SDK built by Marshall X that also

00:05:47.710 --> 00:05:50.110
has some bits of Rust code as well, so it can

00:05:50.110 --> 00:05:52.630
do like really fast DAG Seaboard decoding and

00:05:52.630 --> 00:05:53.680
other stuff.

00:05:53.680 --> 00:05:55.900
So a lot of the technical stuff works really nicely.

00:05:56.740 --> 00:05:59.640
Also, feel free to ask me about things like minimizing hosting

00:05:59.640 --> 00:06:00.120
costs.

00:06:00.120 --> 00:06:01.700
We now use hosting in the EU.

00:06:01.700 --> 00:06:04.430
We got really into hosting on rented VPSs and getting

00:06:04.430 --> 00:06:07.340
a cost down as much as possible and being really, really

00:06:07.340 --> 00:06:08.660
efficient about it.

00:06:08.660 --> 00:06:10.830
Feel free to ask me more about that if you're curious

00:06:10.830 --> 00:06:11.060
.

00:06:11.060 --> 00:06:13.960
And finally, I think one of the most exciting things as

00:06:13.960 --> 00:06:16.920
well about these early stages of the project is that it is

00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:17.820
not just me.

00:06:17.820 --> 00:06:21.180
For over a year now, we've had multiple developers and

00:06:21.180 --> 00:06:25.750
a moderation team working on keeping the feeds going between doing things

00:06:25.750 --> 00:06:29.090
like working on new features and making sure that we kind of

00:06:29.090 --> 00:06:31.860
moderate signups and moderate content on the feeds.

00:06:31.860 --> 00:06:35.500
We also, in kind of September of 2025, we started

00:06:35.500 --> 00:06:39.680
an open collective page, and that happily covers our hosting costs

00:06:39.680 --> 00:06:40.080
.

00:06:40.080 --> 00:06:42.710
It covers also some stickers that I'm going to give away

00:06:42.710 --> 00:06:45.110
later and a little bit of my travel here too, which

00:06:45.110 --> 00:06:46.060
is fantastic.

00:06:46.940 --> 00:06:49.440
And because of that now, we're really becoming a community

00:06:49.440 --> 00:06:51.800
of people who are trying to work on this and trying to

00:06:51.800 --> 00:06:54.900
push AT protocol as a thing that can have purpose for our

00:06:54.900 --> 00:06:56.440
community of science.

00:06:56.440 --> 00:06:59.320
So in the kind of second half of this talk, I

00:06:59.320 --> 00:07:02.760
will talk a little bit more about how we're trying to

00:07:02.760 --> 00:07:07.240
build an ecosystem of tools and move beyond just having feeds.

00:07:07.240 --> 00:07:10.670
So first off, an obvious low-hanging fruit for

00:07:10.670 --> 00:07:12.200
us is PDS hosting.

00:07:12.200 --> 00:07:15.460
We have a PDS running that can host people's data

00:07:15.460 --> 00:07:15.760
.

00:07:15.960 --> 00:07:18.460
The main problem is getting legal situation stuff sorted out.

00:07:18.460 --> 00:07:20.420
I want to do it properly from the start, because if

00:07:20.420 --> 00:07:22.090
we don't do it properly at the start, we'll

00:07:22.090 --> 00:07:23.640
probably never get around to it.

00:07:23.640 --> 00:07:25.950
But we're hoping to start a charity, probably in the

00:07:25.950 --> 00:07:28.300
UK, which would then become the legal host for what we

00:07:28.300 --> 00:07:29.040
're doing.

00:07:29.040 --> 00:07:31.240
And that would then mean that we can host the data of

00:07:31.240 --> 00:07:33.640
astronomers and the astronomy community online.

00:07:33.640 --> 00:07:36.630
I think this is actually something that is maybe a bit of

00:07:36.630 --> 00:07:39.460
a missing niche in the PDS hosting world as well.

00:07:39.460 --> 00:07:41.500
I think people talk a lot about self-hosting,

00:07:41.500 --> 00:07:44.080
and then we also hear a lot about these amazing big projects

00:07:44.080 --> 00:07:47.540
like Black Sky and Euro Sky that are giving us viable alternatives

00:07:47.540 --> 00:07:49.860
to Blue Sky as a place to host your data in the

00:07:49.860 --> 00:07:50.800
atmosphere.

00:07:50.800 --> 00:07:53.510
But I think there's also a missing middle as well for

00:07:53.510 --> 00:07:57.250
kind of distinct communities who want to host data for their community

00:07:57.250 --> 00:07:57.600
.

00:07:58.060 --> 00:07:59.980
I expect we wouldn't be larger than maybe 1,000

00:07:59.980 --> 00:08:01.560
, 2,000 people realistically.

00:08:01.560 --> 00:08:03.930
But because we're kind of a community, I would probably

00:08:03.930 --> 00:08:06.590
already personally know some of the people who are signing up,

00:08:06.590 --> 00:08:08.180
just someone who works in Astro.

00:08:08.840 --> 00:08:11.090
And it's, yeah, it's a kind of nice

00:08:11.090 --> 00:08:13.000
missing middle, I think.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:15.680
And I think it's also great for the health of the

00:08:15.680 --> 00:08:18.770
atmosphere ecosystem, too, if we can have a range of

00:08:18.770 --> 00:08:21.300
PDS hosts and not just have kind of go from one

00:08:21.300 --> 00:08:23.220
to, say, three big hosts.

00:08:23.220 --> 00:08:25.820
I think we want to have a whole spectrum of data hosting

00:08:25.820 --> 00:08:26.500
options.

00:08:26.500 --> 00:08:29.290
And as well as that, if we have our own PD

00:08:29.290 --> 00:08:32.340
S host, then we can define what we want to do

00:08:32.340 --> 00:08:33.940
with data on that.

00:08:33.940 --> 00:08:36.290
And if we have crazy data ideas, then we can do

00:08:36.290 --> 00:08:36.860
those.

00:08:37.540 --> 00:08:40.200
So a couple of weeks ago, we were chatting in a

00:08:40.200 --> 00:08:43.210
meeting and had a cool idea about doing live, real-

00:08:43.210 --> 00:08:44.680
time data streaming.

00:08:44.680 --> 00:08:47.700
The reason why we care about this in astronomy is because when

00:08:47.700 --> 00:08:50.570
a star explodes with something like a supernova, it looks

00:08:50.570 --> 00:08:52.180
a little bit like this here, the Crab Nebula

00:08:52.180 --> 00:08:53.680
, but 1,000 years later.

00:08:53.680 --> 00:08:56.960
But basically, when a star explodes, you want every available

00:08:56.960 --> 00:09:00.520
telescope around the world to point at this place and take data

00:09:00.520 --> 00:09:03.180
and measure things like the afterglow of this event and

00:09:03.180 --> 00:09:05.400
measure other things about it, like how far away it is

00:09:05.400 --> 00:09:07.220
with this redshift, all kinds of other stuff.

00:09:07.240 --> 00:09:10.020
And you want to do that within 30 to 60 seconds of

00:09:10.020 --> 00:09:14.100
this transient event happening or preferably just completely as fast as possible

00:09:14.100 --> 00:09:14.380
.

00:09:14.380 --> 00:09:20.320
There are only certain kinds of detector that will find these things

00:09:20.320 --> 00:09:21.840
happening, but then there's a lot of other kinds of

00:09:21.840 --> 00:09:22.410
telescopes, all with different specialties that you would want to

00:09:22.410 --> 00:09:23.520
know about this and to follow it up right away.

00:09:23.520 --> 00:09:27.650
There are solutions to do this already, but either they have

00:09:27.650 --> 00:09:31.370
some kind of mix of either being older and less secure or

00:09:31.370 --> 00:09:33.820
being very highly centralized.

00:09:33.820 --> 00:09:36.940
In terms of the highly centralized solutions at the moment, a

00:09:36.940 --> 00:09:40.240
lot of different observatories host their own Kafka streams.

00:09:40.740 --> 00:09:42.970
And what that basically means is an observatory, if you

00:09:42.970 --> 00:09:44.800
want to put out data, you need to do things like

00:09:44.800 --> 00:09:47.880
handle authentication for who can subscribe to your Kafka stream.

00:09:47.880 --> 00:09:50.210
You need to set that up, you need to obviously run

00:09:50.210 --> 00:09:53.290
the thing, decide on your schema, continuously run this thing

00:09:53.290 --> 00:09:56.020
and kind of support having many, many different web sockets

00:09:56.020 --> 00:09:59.100
subscribing to that and have as much uptime as possible so

00:09:59.100 --> 00:10:00.660
that people don't have interruptions.

00:10:01.100 --> 00:10:03.650
If you're a consumer then of these Kafka streams, there

00:10:03.650 --> 00:10:06.960
are a lot of different organizations around the world that are producing

00:10:06.960 --> 00:10:10.180
transient events and things that you would want to subscribe to.

00:10:10.180 --> 00:10:12.600
So you then have a lot of different streams that you would

00:10:12.600 --> 00:10:14.650
have to subscribe up to and you'd have to run lots

00:10:14.650 --> 00:10:15.980
of different consumers.

00:10:15.980 --> 00:10:19.820
You have to somehow aggregate all of that data and that can

00:10:19.820 --> 00:10:21.660
get quite complicated.

00:10:21.660 --> 00:10:24.230
Instead with at proto, you can do each one of those

00:10:24.230 --> 00:10:27.310
things with one line of Python code with a new Python package

00:10:27.310 --> 00:10:29.710
that I've done as a hack project in the last week

00:10:29.710 --> 00:10:30.040
.

00:10:30.700 --> 00:10:32.830
Basically, it's called Nebra, it's already on

00:10:32.830 --> 00:10:34.220
PyPy, so if you want to at the end

00:10:34.220 --> 00:10:36.720
of this talk, you can try installing it on your computer

00:10:36.720 --> 00:10:39.140
and try streaming some astronomy transients for yourself.

00:10:39.140 --> 00:10:41.370
If you are a producer, all that you need is an

00:10:41.370 --> 00:10:44.540
account under PDS, set a couple of environment variables for

00:10:44.540 --> 00:10:46.640
your login, and then you just do nebra.

00:10:46.640 --> 00:10:47.260
send.

00:10:47.260 --> 00:10:51.120
That uploads the record to your PDS using the app proto

00:10:51.120 --> 00:10:54.230
SDK behind the scenes, but I've tried to make it

00:10:54.230 --> 00:10:58.860
as sort of simple as possible with the target audience being astronomy

00:10:58.860 --> 00:11:02.960
observatories and astronomy Organizations who do not know anything about

00:11:02.960 --> 00:11:05.740
app proto and they just want a really, really simple Python

00:11:05.740 --> 00:11:07.180
module that just what they need for them.

00:11:07.180 --> 00:11:10.680
Likewise, if you're a consumer, there's a Python

00:11:10.680 --> 00:11:13.990
implementation of a Jetstream client and all you have to do

00:11:13.990 --> 00:11:14.540
is nebra.

00:11:14.540 --> 00:11:18.380
stream and then just pick which collections or handles and different organizations

00:11:18.380 --> 00:11:19.020
you would like.

00:11:19.020 --> 00:11:22.450
What this means now is that a lot of complicated things like

00:11:22.450 --> 00:11:26.790
data authentication and real-time data streaming, even validating

00:11:26.790 --> 00:11:29.740
schemas, they all get handled by the AT protocol because

00:11:29.740 --> 00:11:32.340
we're all here at this amazing conference about this amazing piece

00:11:32.340 --> 00:11:34.580
of software that's been built over the last few years and

00:11:34.580 --> 00:11:35.800
has this amazing dev community.

00:11:36.340 --> 00:11:37.900
All of the hard stuff works.

00:11:37.900 --> 00:11:40.420
All you really need is a Python client just to post and

00:11:40.420 --> 00:11:42.280
receive, which is super simple.

00:11:42.280 --> 00:11:44.660
I can show you as well for the last day or so

00:11:44.660 --> 00:11:47.820
I've been running this and reposting things from NASA

00:11:47.820 --> 00:11:51.680
's General Coordinates Network, which has various different things from

00:11:51.680 --> 00:11:53.160
different NASA based missions.

00:11:53.160 --> 00:11:56.490
This is getting reposted now to a account called transient

00:11:56.490 --> 00:11:58.320
cross poster dot aster sky dot eco.

00:11:58.660 --> 00:12:00.120
This is just on pdsls now we can go

00:12:00.120 --> 00:12:02.200
look at some of these different records.

00:12:02.200 --> 00:12:04.400
I know there's gravitational waves here.

00:12:04.400 --> 00:12:05.300
They're not actually real.

00:12:05.300 --> 00:12:08.170
They're testing their pipeline before the big gravitational wave thing starts

00:12:08.170 --> 00:12:08.740
happening.

00:12:08.740 --> 00:12:10.900
But like we can see records like that.

00:12:10.900 --> 00:12:13.870
If I can do the back button here, let's find

00:12:13.870 --> 00:12:14.300
it.

00:12:14.300 --> 00:12:15.040
Where was one?

00:12:15.040 --> 00:12:18.140
There's these are all the gravitational wave ones.

00:12:18.140 --> 00:12:20.550
I think, yeah, this is a juicy and circular where

00:12:20.550 --> 00:12:22.720
people can write things and stuff.

00:12:22.720 --> 00:12:25.860
And this is all basically existing data that's now getting stream

00:12:25.860 --> 00:12:28.420
ed on the ad proto and anyone can go find that and

00:12:28.420 --> 00:12:30.840
go look at that and what's best as well is that

00:12:30.840 --> 00:12:32.800
this Python module is obviously open source.

00:12:32.800 --> 00:12:36.630
You can install it with Python and anyone could start working with

00:12:36.630 --> 00:12:39.020
any data that they'd like and streaming that in any way

00:12:39.020 --> 00:12:39.640
that they'd like.

00:12:39.640 --> 00:12:43.580
For instance, this is originally designed for astronomy, but it

00:12:43.580 --> 00:12:46.420
can ingest or produce any type of record that you'd

00:12:46.420 --> 00:12:46.720
like.

00:12:46.720 --> 00:12:49.600
For instance, within the last week, a record called Mat

00:12:49.600 --> 00:12:51.560
adisco was recently released.

00:12:51.560 --> 00:12:53.830
I think Robin might talk about it a little bit in his

00:12:53.830 --> 00:12:55.020
talk later this week.

00:12:55.500 --> 00:12:58.750
It's a very simple schema for posting metadata of science data

00:12:58.750 --> 00:12:59.000
.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:01.950
And if you want to, you can stream that too with

00:13:01.950 --> 00:13:04.580
this one line of Python code, which is really nice and

00:13:04.580 --> 00:13:04.980
easy.

00:13:04.980 --> 00:13:08.980
And the idea really is to make this a super simple solution

00:13:08.980 --> 00:13:12.400
that people can just go and use if they care about real

00:13:12.400 --> 00:13:13.480
time data streaming.

00:13:13.480 --> 00:13:15.580
And they don't even have to care too much about that

00:13:15.580 --> 00:13:16.520
it's AT protocol.

00:13:16.520 --> 00:13:18.860
They don't have to know about what Jetstream is or

00:13:18.860 --> 00:13:20.460
what a PDS is to get started.

00:13:20.460 --> 00:13:23.040
So yeah, thanks very much.

