Maybe we can, this time we can start here with Matt

00:13:45.540 --> 00:13:45.860
.

00:13:50.200 --> 00:13:53.080
This is very exciting and wonderful to hear.

00:13:53.080 --> 00:13:57.600
So this last part about having scientists on AT Proto,

00:13:57.600 --> 00:14:01.980
what kind of appetite have you seen so far for people sharing

00:14:01.980 --> 00:14:08.600
measurements or research observations that would otherwise or eventually go on the

00:14:08.600 --> 00:14:11.960
archive or other types of publications?

00:14:12.680 --> 00:14:16.030
So I think that there's been pretty much no appetite for

00:14:16.030 --> 00:14:16.860
it so far.

00:14:16.860 --> 00:14:18.490
I don't think I've seen it be very well explored

00:14:18.490 --> 00:14:18.680
.

00:14:18.680 --> 00:14:20.870
I think Matt at Disco is the first time I've

00:14:20.870 --> 00:14:23.700
really seen someone do it at scale and I'm not familiar

00:14:23.700 --> 00:14:25.960
with that many other groups doing it.

00:14:25.960 --> 00:14:28.400
I think it's a kind of thing where it takes some

00:14:28.400 --> 00:14:31.700
sort of amount of knowledge to be able to bridge the knowledge

00:14:31.700 --> 00:14:33.450
gap and know, okay, at Proto, it's

00:14:33.450 --> 00:14:35.480
a thing people might have heard of it if they've been

00:14:35.480 --> 00:14:36.180
on Blue Sky.

00:14:36.280 --> 00:14:38.560
But it's another thing entirely to understand the primitives and

00:14:38.560 --> 00:14:40.400
know, okay, this is something that can work in real

00:14:40.400 --> 00:14:40.820
time.

00:14:40.820 --> 00:14:43.060
We can self-host the data with the PDS.

00:14:43.060 --> 00:14:45.180
We can rely on the relays and these bits of software

00:14:45.180 --> 00:14:45.820
and stuff.

00:14:45.820 --> 00:14:48.780
So I think it requires people to try and bridge the gap

00:14:48.780 --> 00:14:52.370
and sort of make it really, really easy for scientists because

00:14:52.370 --> 00:14:55.540
I actually don't think there's much investment at all in

00:14:55.540 --> 00:14:58.460
doing real-time data streaming and stuff.

00:14:58.460 --> 00:15:00.510
And also as well, you mentioned this being on the archive

00:15:00.510 --> 00:15:00.720
.

00:15:00.720 --> 00:15:02.780
Most of this data doesn't end up on the archive,

00:15:02.780 --> 00:15:04.540
but papers will be written about it.

00:15:04.540 --> 00:15:07.320
So it's somewhere in between where it's very small bits

00:15:07.320 --> 00:15:10.270
of data with, say, like a potential location of something

00:15:10.270 --> 00:15:10.480
.

00:15:10.480 --> 00:15:12.430
And it's up to people to deal with that how they

00:15:12.430 --> 00:15:12.980
want to.

00:15:12.980 --> 00:15:14.640
Okay.

