So I admit to it being kind of post-launch

00:15:24.070 --> 00:15:24.300
.

00:15:24.300 --> 00:15:26.000
Brain's not fully there.

00:15:26.640 --> 00:15:31.860
Is the intent to have conversations about the science here?

00:15:31.860 --> 00:15:34.920
Is the intent to actually be hosting the science here?

00:15:34.920 --> 00:15:35.840
Is it both?

00:15:35.840 --> 00:15:38.280
I'm curious kind of what you're trying to do.

00:15:38.280 --> 00:15:40.800
So I guess in that sense, I've kind of shown

00:15:40.800 --> 00:15:44.090
stuff that's doing all of the above because the feeds are

00:15:44.090 --> 00:15:48.430
a space for people to have conversations about astronomy and other things

00:15:48.430 --> 00:15:48.700
.

00:15:49.380 --> 00:15:51.470
And then this newer project with, say, NEBRE

00:15:51.470 --> 00:15:53.620
F, for instance, or PDS hosting are more about

00:15:53.620 --> 00:15:56.900
hosting either bits of scientific data or hosting people's social data

00:15:56.900 --> 00:15:58.960
if they're in the astronomy community.

00:15:58.960 --> 00:16:02.530
So kind of a whole different range of little applications of app

00:16:02.530 --> 00:16:04.920
proto specifically for astronomers.

00:16:04.920 --> 00:16:05.540
Thank you.

00:16:05.540 --> 00:16:07.580
Matthew?

00:16:08.320 --> 00:16:11.900
That's really inspiring work.

00:16:11.900 --> 00:16:12.540
I love it.

00:16:12.540 --> 00:16:13.980
Just a couple of things.

00:16:13.980 --> 00:16:18.070
How many institutions do you think are open to the idea of

00:16:18.070 --> 00:16:19.540
setting up a PDS?

00:16:19.540 --> 00:16:22.460
Is that a hard argument to make?

00:16:22.460 --> 00:16:23.760
Or did you find it really easy?

00:16:23.760 --> 00:16:25.740
I've been told to expect a lot of resistance.

00:16:25.740 --> 00:16:29.370
I could see there being some amount of resistance, but I

00:16:29.370 --> 00:16:31.020
'm honestly not sure.

00:16:31.020 --> 00:16:34.530
I think that the challenge is selling what a PDS is

00:16:34.530 --> 00:16:38.230
and making it, just really making it clear why it's

00:16:38.230 --> 00:16:39.580
so important.

00:16:39.580 --> 00:16:43.670
Because I think that universities, we talked about this the other

00:16:43.670 --> 00:16:46.200
day, how I feel like they have, it takes a

00:16:46.200 --> 00:16:48.400
lot of, they have a lot of mass.

00:16:48.400 --> 00:16:49.720
It's hard to get them to move.

00:16:49.720 --> 00:16:50.880
It's hard to get them to have momentum.

00:16:52.380 --> 00:16:56.080
But equally, a lot of universities in Europe, especially in

00:16:56.080 --> 00:16:59.350
the German-speaking world, say my university, I did

00:16:59.350 --> 00:17:02.390
my PhD in Germany and my one now in Austria, they

00:17:02.390 --> 00:17:04.160
are all not on X anymore.

00:17:04.160 --> 00:17:07.370
And they are all exclusively on Blue Sky and other non-

00:17:07.370 --> 00:17:08.840
fascist platforms.

00:17:08.840 --> 00:17:12.790
So I think that they have, within certain circles at these

00:17:12.790 --> 00:17:14.900
universities, they care.

00:17:14.900 --> 00:17:17.680
I think the challenge really is explaining what a PDS is

00:17:17.680 --> 00:17:20.390
to these different groups and trying to get the buy-in

00:17:20.390 --> 00:17:23.580
and really kind of distilling it away from being very technical

00:17:23.580 --> 00:17:24.460
language.

00:17:24.460 --> 00:17:26.220
Because I kind of show some parts of our project to people

00:17:26.220 --> 00:17:27.540
and they're like, oh, yeah, okay, that

00:17:27.540 --> 00:17:28.040
's nice.

00:17:28.040 --> 00:17:28.960
But I don't think they get it.

00:17:28.960 --> 00:17:31.760
The challenge really is selling the thing.

