I also thinking, I mean, obviously this might not be

00:17:39.210 --> 00:17:42.180
a huge issue in astronomy, but the ability to be able

00:17:42.180 --> 00:17:44.880
to live stream your data like this could really open up.

00:17:44.900 --> 00:17:46.460
citizen science in a major way.

00:17:46.460 --> 00:17:47.800
Have you ever considered that?

00:17:47.800 --> 00:17:50.550
I mean, obviously not for people who are hunting for super

00:17:50.550 --> 00:17:52.430
nova, but I mean, there's a lot of other

00:17:52.430 --> 00:17:55.380
areas of science where citizen science has a little role to play

00:17:55.380 --> 00:17:55.740
.

00:17:55.740 --> 00:17:58.670
And it might sort of lower the barrier to entry for people

00:17:58.670 --> 00:18:00.520
to share their data in this way.

00:18:00.520 --> 00:18:01.920
That is such a cool idea.

00:18:01.920 --> 00:18:05.180
Imagine if someone made an app where you can, things like

00:18:05.180 --> 00:18:08.420
Merlin, if you know of the bird identification app,

00:18:08.420 --> 00:18:11.750
imagine if Merlin posted every bird that it finds on the

00:18:11.750 --> 00:18:12.620
app proto.

00:18:12.780 --> 00:18:15.250
And every time someone sees it, it gets put on a

00:18:15.250 --> 00:18:15.700
PDS.

00:18:15.700 --> 00:18:18.220
And then you kind of have this, if you're an

00:18:18.220 --> 00:18:21.470
ornithologist, for instance, you have this massive

00:18:21.470 --> 00:18:25.180
citizen scientist data set of people identifying birds.

00:18:25.180 --> 00:18:26.600
It doesn't just have to be Merlin.

00:18:26.600 --> 00:18:28.790
Other people could reuse the schema with their own app or their

00:18:28.790 --> 00:18:29.460
own anything.

00:18:29.460 --> 00:18:31.220
Really, the possibilities are there.

00:18:31.220 --> 00:18:33.530
Again, I think the hard part is the bridge from,

